## Dealing With Missing Data

---

![inline][missing_features_bar_chart]

---

## Filling in Missing Categorical Data

```python
train_data['PoolQC'].fillna('None')
```

^ Pretty easy. You can usually just fill in a single dummy value.

---

## Filling in Missing Continuous Data

---

> MasVnrType: Masonry veneer type
> MasVnrArea: Masonry veneer area in square feet

```python
train_data['MasVnrArea'].fillna(0.0)
```

---

```python
train_data.loc[train_data['GarageYrBlt'].isnull(), 'GarageYrBlt'] = \
  train_data.loc[train_data['GarageYrBlt'].isnull(), 'YearBuilt']
```

^ More tricky. You have to think about what a reasonable fill-in would be.
^ Impute by neighborhood (fill in with mean for neighborhood)
^ Fill in with YearBuilt
^ Train regressor to predict GarageYrBlt and use its predictions for missing values
